5 Sec. 7. 1. The Public Records Task Force is hereby created.
6 The Task Force consists of the following 10 members:
7 (a) One government representative and two transparency
8 advocates appointed by the Majority Leader of the Senate;
9 (b) Two government representatives and one transparency
10 advocate appointed by the Speaker of the Assembly;
11 (c) One government representative appointed by the Minority
12 Leader of the Senate;
13 (d) One transparency advocate appointed by the Minority
14 Leader of the Assembly; and
15 (e) One government representative and one transparency
16 advocate appointed by the Governor.
17 2. The Task Force shall:
18 (a) Evaluate:
19 (1) Current exemptions to chapter 239 of NRS;
20 (2) The impact of broad requests for public records on
21 governmental entities;
22 (3) The cost, burden and time constraint on governmental
23 entities to redact confidential information;
24 (4) The financial burden on a person who requests a public
25 record;
26 (5) Mechanisms to resolve disputes involving requests for
27 public records, including, without limitation, mediation and other
28 types of alternative dispute resolution; and
29 (6) Methods for collecting and sharing data related to
30 requests for public records.
31 (b) Make recommendations, including, without limitation:
32 (1) To clarify the custodianship and control of public
33 records;
34 (2) To protect sensitive information while promoting
35 government transparency;
36 (3) To identify situations in which access to public records
37 should be granted or denied;
38 (4) For penalties to impose against governmental entities for
39 providing delayed or incomplete responses to a request for public
40 records;
41 (5) For protocols to protect personal information and
42 criminal investigations;
43 (6) For a standardized fee schedule; and
44 (7) For mechanisms to protect governmental entities from
45 retaliatory litigation.
