1 3. The members of the Task Force serve without
2 compensation.
3 4. Each member of the Task Force who is an officer or
4 employee of the State or local government must be relieved from his
5 or her duties without loss of regular compensation so that the
6 member may prepare for and attend meetings of the Task Force and
7 perform any work necessary to carry out the duties of the Task
8 Force in the most timely manner practicable. A state agency or local
9 government shall not require an officer or employee who is a
10 member of the Task Force to make up the time the member is absent
11 from work to carry out his or her duties as a member, and shall not
12 require the member to take annual, vacation or compensatory time
13 for the absence.
14 5. The Task Force shall, at its first meeting, elect a Chair from
15 the members who are transparency advocates and a Vice Chair from
16 the members who are government representatives.
17 6. The Task Force shall meet:
18 (a) Upon the call of the Chair or a majority of the members of
19 the Task Force; and
20 (b) At least four times.
21 7. A majority of the members of the Task Force constitutes a
22 quorum for the transaction of business, and a majority of those
23 members present at the meeting is sufficient for any official action
24 taken by the Task Force.
25 8. The Task Force may apply for and accept any gift, donation,
26 bequest, grant or other source of money to carry out the duties of the
27 Task Force.
28 9. On or before October 31, 2026, the Task Force shall prepare
29 and submit a written report to the Director of the Legislative
30 Counsel Bureau for transmittal to the Joint Interim Standing
31 Committee on Government Affairs and the Senate and Assembly
32 Standing Committees on Government Affairs for the 84th Session
33 of the Legislature. The report must include, without limitation, a
34 summary of the work and recommendations of the Task Force.
35 10. As used in this section:
36 (a) “Governmental entity” has the meaning ascribed to it in
37 NRS 239.005.
38 (b) “Government representative” includes, without limitation, a
39 representative:
40 (1) From the Nevada Association of Counties or a county;
41 (2) From the Nevada League of Cities or a local government;
42 (3) Who is a district attorney or city attorney;
43 (4) From a law enforcement agency;
44 (5) From a school district;
45 (6) From the Office of the Attorney General;
